**Despite recent rain, farmers in Virginia struggle with effects of summer drought**
Despite recent rain, farmers in Virginia are still struggling with the effects of summer drought. Morgan Slaven, a sheep farmer in Augusta County, said she was grateful for her 'off-farm job' to generate income after drought conditions presented back-to-back years of challenges ahead of this year's harvest season. 'What if I lost my job?' Slaven said. 'The only reason I have this place right now is because I have an off-the-farm income.' The drought, which was exacerbated by temperatures reaching 99 degrees and no rain in the Lynchburg area, has impacted profits in the largest economic sector in the state, with agriculture contributing about $82.3 billion annually to the economy. According to the Virginia Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services, agriculture employs over 381,800 people. Assistance programs are available, but some farmers may be reluctant to use them, and they may only allow farmers to break even. 'People have a lot of pride, they don’t want to take donations, but it’s there, because your tax dollars are paying for it,' Slaven said. The drought has hurt sheep farmers, corn, and bean commodities, with corn yields estimated to be 36.1 million bushels, down 38% from the 2023 level. 'It’s a half a crop at best, and it’s highly damaged,' said Robert Harper, a grain marketing specialist at the Virginia Farm Bureau. 'It’s a year of extremes. It seems like we’re just getting these cyclical weather patterns, and we get stuck in them.'
