**‘5,3m people suffering from acute food insecurity'**
According to the World Food Programme (WFP) Food Security and Markets Monitoring Report, at least 5.3 million people in Zimbabwe are suffering from acute food insecurity due to the severe drought caused by El Niño weather conditions. The report states that the number of people facing insufficient food consumption is estimated at 5.3 million during the last week of July 2024, with 5.9 million rural people and 1.7 million people in urban areas facing hunger. The drought has led to poor harvests after the 2023/24 agricultural season, with 46% of the rural population estimated to be food insecure. The WFP survey also found that 8.1 million people are resorting to crisis and above food-based coping strategies, with 52% of the population estimated to be food insecure in July 2024. President Emmerson Mnangagwa declared the drought a national disaster in May, extending a US$3 billion begging bowl for humanitarian assistance.
